{"title_page": "Chris Morris (activist)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n'''Chris Morris''' (born 23 May 1979) is an [[activist]] who, with Euan Sutherland, successfully challenged the British Government in the [[European Court of Human Rights]] and secured an equal [[age of consent]] for sexual activity between males.<ref>Coming out of the shadows, ''[[The Guardian]]'', 8 October 1997</ref> He went on to study psychology and work as a political speechwriter and consultant.<ref>[http://www.evolver-talent.com/2011/06/chris-morris-interview-part-1/ Interview with Chris Morris] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110914013050/http://www.evolver-talent.com/2011/06/chris-morris-interview-part-1/ |date=14 September 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==The equal age of consent campaign==\nWhen male [[homosexuality]] was decriminalised in [[England and Wales]] in 1967, the age of consent was set at 21. It was lowered to 18 in 1994, but Morris and Sutherland took their case to Europe to demand it be reduced further to 16, the same age as it is for heterosexuals. They invoked Articles 8 and 19 of the [[European Convention on Human Rights]], which guarantee the right to a private life and protection from discrimination.<ref>[http://www.stonewall.org.uk/information_bank/criminal_law/66.asp Information Bank: Age of Consent \u2013 Changing the Law] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070105015547/http://www.stonewall.org.uk/information_bank/criminal_law/66.asp |date=5 January 2007 }} from [[Stonewall (UK)|Stonewall]]; accessed 17 February 2007</ref>\n\nTheir case was originally backed by the [[gay rights]] group [[Stonewall (UK)|Stonewall]] and later Morris formed his own organisation, [[YouthSpeak]], which was funded by Sir [[Ian McKellen]]. YouthSpeak sent delegations of teenagers to meet MPs and the media to tell their personal stories about how an unequal age of consent affected their lives. The group also projected a laser beam onto [[Big Ben]] demanding \"16 for everyone\" and delivered a 25,000-strong petition to new prime minister [[Tony Blair]] when he was elected in May 1997.<ref>http://www.queeryouth.org.uk/community/index.php?act=Issues&CODE=83&ISSUE=Timeline</ref>\n\nOpposition to the campaign was led by [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] peer [[Janet Young, Baroness Young|Baroness Young]] and the then [[Archbishop of Canterbury]], [[George Carey]], among others.<ref>[http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-7441/Row-gay-age-consent.html Row over gay age of consent]</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/317364.stm Peers prepare for gay consent clash ]</ref>\n\nIn July 1997, the European Court found that the existence of different ages of consent was discriminatory and that no valid grounds existed to justify that discrimination.  They therefore found that the age of consent for homosexual acts should be lowered to 16. In arriving at their conclusion, the court cited their reasoning in the previous cases, ''[[Dudgeon v United Kingdom]]'' and ''[[Norris v. Ireland]]''.\n\nIn response to the court's findings, the then [[Home Secretary]] [[Jack Straw]] agreed with Sutherland and Morris that a Bill would be proposed to Parliament in the summer of 1998 to reduce the age of consent for homosexual acts to 16. The Court approved their \"friendly settlement\".<ref>[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm199798/cmhansrd/vo980622/debtext/80622-21.htm Hansard Debates for 22 June 1998: Column 756]</ref>\n\nAfter two defeats in the [[House of Lords]], the law was eventually changed as part of the [[Sexual Offences (Amendment) Act 2000]], after the use of the [[Parliament Acts 1911 and 1949]], in November 2000.\n\n==Other gay activism==\nIn 1998, Morris became a member of [[OutRage!]] and in 1999 he founded and became editor of the gay rights magazine ''[[Outcast (magazine)|Outcast]]''.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Waites, Matthew.|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/69403652|title=The age of consent : young people, sexuality, and citizenship|date=2005|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|isbn=978-0-230-50593-3|location=Houndmills, Basingstoke, Hampshire|oclc=69403652}}</ref> Contributors included left-wing [[Mayor of London]] [[Ken Livingstone]], [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Lib Dem]] leader [[Charles Kennedy]], [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office|Foreign Office]] minister [[Ben Bradshaw]], ''Anti-Gay'' author [[Mark Simpson (journalist)|Mark Simpson]] and veteran activist [[Peter Tatchell]]. The magazine satirised and was critical of many gay activists and businesses and Morris was criticised for \"biting the hand that fed him\" during his age of consent campaign.<ref>[http://gaymafiawatch.wordpress.com/2010/03/26/whatever-happened-to-chris-morris/ Whatever happened to Chris Morris?]</ref>\n\nWith OutRage!, he broke into [[Lambeth Palace]] and confronted the then [[Archbishop of Canterbury]], [[George Carey]], about his opposition to an equal age of consent. With Peter Tatchell and two others, he attempted a [[citizen's arrest]] on President [[Robert Mugabe]] to publicise Mugabe's alleged role in the torture of two opposition journalists (Mark Chavunduka and Ray Choto) in [[Zimbabwe]]. He was himself arrested but later released without charge.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/558385.stm Tatchell 'vindicated' as charges dropped], ''[[BBC News Online]]'', 10 December 1999; accessed 17 February 2007</ref>\n\nIn November 2012, Morris wrote an essay on his website (republished by ''[[The Guardian]]'') discussing gay identity, where he said that \"I don't think I'm Gay any more; I just know I'm in love with a wonderful man. And that is why I support [[same-sex marriage]], because love transcends everything and it doesn't matter who you love as long as you love.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Morris|first1=Chris|title=Why I'm no longer Gay but still want to marry a man|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2012/nov/02/gay-marry-man|accessdate=16 April 2017|work=The Guardian|date=2 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Stonewall (charity)]]\n* [[OutRage!]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.chrismorris.com Official website]\n* [http://www.chrismorris.com/blog/2011/05/are-we-sure-that-being-gay-isnt-a-choice/ Are we sure that being gay isn't a choice?]\n* [http://www.gaydarnation.com/UserPortal/Article/Detail.aspx?ID=19404 Interview with Chris Morris], ''Gaydar Nation'', September 2007\n* [http://www.newstatesman.com/199902120019 Now meet the real gay mafia], ''[[New Statesman]]'', February 1999\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Morris, Chris}}\n[[Category:LGBT rights activists from England]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from England]]\n[[Category:English human rights activists]]\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Gay writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n'''Chris Morris''' (born 23 May 1979) is an [[activist]] who, with Euan Sutherland, successfully challenged the British Government in the [[European Court of Human Rights]] and secured an equal [[age of consent]] for sexual activity between males.<ref>Coming out of the shadows, ''[[The Guardian]]'', 8 October 1997</ref> He went on to study psychology and work as a political speechwriter and consultant.<ref>[http://www.evolver-talent.com/2011/06/chris-morris-interview-part-1/ Interview with Chris Morris] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110914013050/http://www.evolver-talent.com/2011/06/chris-morris-interview-part-1/ |date=14 September 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==The equal age of consent campaign==\nWhen male [[homosexuality]] was decriminalised in [[England and Wales]] in 1967, the age of consent was set at 21. It was lowered to 18 in 1994, but Morris and Sutherland took their case to Europe to demand it be reduced further to 16, the same age as it is for heterosexuals. They invoked Articles 8 and 19 of the [[European Convention on Human Rights]], which guarantee the right to a private life and protection from discrimination.<ref>[http://www.stonewall.org.uk/information_bank/criminal_law/66.asp Information Bank: Age of Consent \u2013 Changing the Law] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070105015547/http://www.stonewall.org.uk/information_bank/criminal_law/66.asp |date=5 January 2007 }} from [[Stonewall (UK)|Stonewall]]; accessed 17 February 2007</ref>\n\nTheir case was originally backed by the [[gay rights]] group [[Stonewall (UK)|Stonewall]] and later Morris formed his own organisation, [[YouthSpeak]], which was funded by Sir [[Ian McKellen]]. YouthSpeak sent delegations of teenagers to meet MPs and the media to tell their personal stories about how an unequal age of consent affected their lives. The group also projected a laser beam onto [[Big Ben]] demanding \"16 for everyone\" and delivered a 25,000-strong petition to new prime minister [[Tony Blair]] when he was elected in May 1997.<ref>http://www.queeryouth.org.uk/community/index.php?act=Issues&CODE=83&ISSUE=Timeline</ref>\n\nOpposition to the campaign was led by [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] peer [[Janet Young, Baroness Young|Baroness Young]] and the then [[Archbishop of Canterbury]], [[George Carey]], among others.<ref>[http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-7441/Row-gay-age-consent.html Row over gay age of consent]</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/317364.stm Peers prepare for gay consent clash ]</ref>\n\nIn July 1997, the European Court found that the existence of different ages of consent was discriminatory and that no valid grounds existed to justify that discrimination.  They therefore found that the age of consent for homosexual acts should be lowered to 16. In arriving at their conclusion, the court cited their reasoning in the previous cases, ''[[Dudgeon v United Kingdom]]'' and ''[[Norris v. Ireland]]''.\n\nIn response to the court's findings, the then [[Home Secretary]] [[Jack Straw]] agreed with Sutherland and Morris that a Bill would be proposed to Parliament in the summer of 1998 to reduce the age of consent for homosexual acts to 16. The Court approved their \"friendly settlement\".<ref>[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm199798/cmhansrd/vo980622/debtext/80622-21.htm Hansard Debates for 22 June 1998: Column 756]</ref>\n\nAfter two defeats in the [[House of Lords]], the law was eventually changed as part of the [[Sexual Offences (Amendment) Act 2000]], after the use of the [[Parliament Acts 1911 and 1949]], in November 2000.\n\n==Other gay activism==\nIn 1998, Morris became a member of [[OutRage!]] and in 1999 he founded and became editor of the gay rights magazine ''[[Outcast (magazine)|Outcast]]''.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Waites, Matthew.|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/69403652|title=The age of consent : young people, sexuality, and citizenship|date=2005|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|isbn=978-0-230-50593-3|location=Houndmills, Basingstoke, Hampshire|oclc=69403652}}</ref> Contributors included left-wing [[Mayor of London]] [[Ken Livingstone]], [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Lib Dem]] leader [[Charles Kennedy]], [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office|Foreign Office]] minister [[Ben Bradshaw]], ''Anti-Gay'' author [[Mark Simpson (journalist)|Mark Simpson]] and veteran activist [[Peter Tatchell]]. The magazine satirised and was critical of many gay activists and businesses and Morris was criticised for \"biting the hand that fed him\" during his age of consent campaign.<ref>[http://gaymafiawatch.wordpress.com/2010/03/26/whatever-happened-to-chris-morris/ Whatever happened to Chris Morris?]</ref>\n\nWith OutRage!, he broke into [[Lambeth Palace]] and confronted the then [[Archbishop of Canterbury]], [[George Carey]], about his opposition to an equal age of consent. With Peter Tatchell and two others, he attempted a [[citizen's arrest]] on President [[Robert Mugabe]] to publicise Mugabe's alleged role in the torture of two opposition journalists (Mark Chavunduka and Ray Choto) in [[Zimbabwe]]. He was himself arrested but later released without charge.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/558385.stm Tatchell 'vindicated' as charges dropped], ''[[BBC News Online]]'', 10 December 1999; accessed 17 February 2007</ref>\n\nIn November 2012, Morris wrote an essay on his website (republished by ''[[The Guardian]]'') discussing gay identity, where he said that \"I don't think I'm Gay any more; I just know I'm in love with a wonderful man. And that is why I support [[same-sex marriage]], because love transcends everything and it doesn't matter who you love as long as you love.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Morris|first1=Chris|title=Why I'm no longer Gay but still want to marry a man|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2012/nov/02/gay-marry-man|accessdate=16 April 2017|work=The Guardian|date=2 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Stonewall (charity)]]\n* [[OutRage!]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.chrismorris.com Official website]\n* [http://www.chrismorris.com/blog/2011/05/are-we-sure-that-being-gay-isnt-a-choice/ Are we sure that being gay isn't a choice?]\n* [http://www.gaydarnation.com/UserPortal/Article/Detail.aspx?ID=19404 Interview with Chris Morris], ''Gaydar Nation'', September 2007\n* [http://www.newstatesman.com/199902120019 Now meet the real gay mafia], ''[[New Statesman]]'', February 1999\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Morris, Chris}}\n[[Category:LGBT rights activists from England]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from England]]\n[[Category:English human rights activists]]\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Gay writers]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chris_Morris_(activist)"}
